17 anteibat with acc. is still rare in Cicero (c. g. Acad. Post. 9, ,35 Brut. 64, 229), who uses the verb absolutely, as Caesar, or with the dative. Beginning with Nepos, Sallust and Livy, the accusa- tive becomes the more usual, and so in Tac. who has the absolute construction eight times, but the dative only once: Anu. V 3. See Lex. Tac. s. v. and Heraeus to H. 145. cf. also Tac. Ann. XV 60 quem . . . in animo principis anteibat.
